   "id": "3cfd66b8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Overview of respiration data preprocessing and analysis\n",
    "This tutorial covers a basic pipeline for preprocessing and analysis of respiration data collected during a experimental task. It introduces core `pyriodic` classes.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "At first, we import the necessary Python modules:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "25447951",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pickle\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "from pyriodic.preproc import RawSignal\n",
    "from pyriodic.viz import plot_phase_diagnostics, CircPlot\n",
    "from pyriodic.phase_events import create_phase_events"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ee63f33e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Load in data and create `RawSignal` object\n",
    "\n",
    "The first step is to load in the respiration time series data. Together with the sampling frequency, this is used to create a `RawSignal` object. This object holds many useful methods for preprocessing the raw data. \n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "d8ef4072",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# load data\n",
    "with open(\"../../data/respiration/example.pkl\", \"rb\") as file:\n",
    "    data = pickle.load(file)\n",
    "\n",
    "# extract respiration timeseries and sampling frequency\n",
    "resp_ts = data[\"respiration_timeseries\"].get_data().squeeze()\n",
    "sfreq = data[\"respiration_timeseries\"].info[\"sfreq\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# initialise RawSignal object\n",
    "raw = RawSignal(resp_ts, fs=sfreq)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ea97deca",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The `RawSignal` object has a built-in plotting method that allows you to visualise the data. You can specify the start time and duration of the segment you want to plot. If no arguments are provided, it will plot the first 20 seconds of the signal. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "954ab9ee",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<Axes: xlabel='Time (s)', ylabel='Amplitude'>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 3,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "raw.plot(start=20, duration=20)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "692eeace",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Preprocessing\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "7644d7bd",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<Axes: xlabel='Time (s)', ylabel='Amplitude'>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 4,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "raw.filter_bandpass(low = 0.1, high = 1)\n",
    "raw.plot(start=20, duration=20)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "361bbb2e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<Axes: xlabel='Time (s)', ylabel='Amplitude'>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 5,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "raw.smoothing(window_size=50)\n",
    "raw.plot(start=20, duration=20)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "e177433d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<Axes: xlabel='Time (s)', ylabel='Amplitude'>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "raw.zscore()\n",
    "raw.plot(start=20, duration=20)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3e72a337",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As the data is modified in-place, the original signal is lost. If you want to keep the original signal, make a copy before applying any modifications. To see which modifications have been applied to the signal, you can print the history:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "db52ddfe",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "['bandpass(0.1 Hz - 1 Hz)',\n",
       " 'Smoothing has been applied with a window size of 50',\n",
       " 'zscore()']"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 7,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "raw.history"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "04e6ad2f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Extract phase angles\n",
    "There are several ways to extract phase angles from the respiration signal. We will use the recommended two-point method, which linearly interpolates the signal from peak to trough from $0$ to $\\pi$. and trough to peak from $\\pi$ to $2\\pi$.\n",
    "\n",
    "For a review of the different methods, see the [phase extraction tutorial](02_phase_extraction.ipynb)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "ba4c037b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "phase, peaks, troughs = raw.phase_twopoint(prominence=0.1, distance=0.5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "63003f5d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "(<Figure size 1200x500 with 4 Axes>,\n",
       " array([<Axes: >, <Axes: ylabel='Two-point'>], dtype=object))"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plot_phase_diagnostics(\n",
    "            {\"Two-point\": phase},\n",
    "            start = 20,\n",
    "            window_duration = 20,\n",
    "            fs = raw.fs,\n",
    "            data = raw.ts, #the preproccessed data \n",
    "            peaks=peaks,\n",
    "            troughs=troughs\n",
    "        )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0490227c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we will extract the phase angles corresponding to the events of interest. This will allow us to analyse the whether the respiration phase is aligned with the timing of the stimuli presented during the task. \n",
    "\n",
    "To acheive this, we first need to get the event timings. In the data used for this tutorial, the events are stored in a numpy array with $n$ rows and 3 columns. The first column holds the the sample index of the event, and the third column holds the trigger value (i.e. an integer that identifes the type of event)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "48750c9e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Triggers: [  3   5   9  35  37  41 416   3   5   9]\n",
      "Sample indices: [121550 122000 122449 122891 123329 123797 124246 124920 125370 125819]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "events = data[\"events\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "trigger_vals = events[:, 2]\n",
    "sample_indices = events[:, 0]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Triggers:\", trigger_vals[:10])\n",
    "print(\"Sample indices:\", sample_indices[:10])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ec95811c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To make it easier to understand the data, we will convert the trigger values into a list of event names."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "37e04efb",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Event labels: ['salient/first', 'salient/second', 'salient/third', 'salient/irregular/fourth', 'salient/irregular/fifth', 'salient/irregular/sixth', 'omission/target/irregular/hit', 'salient/first', 'salient/second', 'salient/third']\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "event_ids = {\n",
    "    # stimulus leading up to the target stimulus \n",
    "    ## all are salient, but the fourth, fifth and sixth can be either regular or irregular \n",
    "    ## (i.e. they are either presented at the expected time or jittered)\n",
    "    3: \"salient/first\",\n",
    "    5: \"salient/second\",\n",
    "    9: \"salient/third\",\n",
    "    19: \"salient/regular/fourth\",\n",
    "    21: \"salient/regular/fifth\",\n",
    "    25: \"salient/regular/sixth\",\n",
    "    35: \"salient/irregular/fourth\",\n",
    "    37: \"salient/irregular/fifth\",\n",
    "    41: \"salient/irregular/sixth\",\n",
    "\n",
    "    # target stimulus\n",
    "    ## can either be weak or omission\n",
    "    ## the regular and irregular is used to indicate whether the proceeding stimulus was presented at the expected time or jittered\n",
    "    ## the target is always presented at the expected time\n",
    "    337: \"weak/target/regular/hit\",\n",
    "    593: \"weak/target/regular/miss\",\n",
    "    353: \"weak/target/irregular/hit\",\n",
    "    609: \"weak/target/irregular/miss\",\n",
    "    400: \"omission/target/regular/hit\",\n",
    "    416: \"omission/target/irregular/hit\",\n",
    "    656: \"omission/target/regular/miss\",\n",
    "    672: \"omission/target/irregular/miss\",\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "event_labels = [event_ids.get(trig, \"unknown\") for trig in trigger_vals]\n",
    "print(f\"Event labels: {event_labels[:10]}\")    "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8ce074e5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now that we have our event labels and the phase angles, we can find the phase angles corresponding to the experimental events."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "01b25739",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Rejected 0 out of 2100 events (0.0%)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circ = create_phase_events(\n",
    "    phase_ts=phase,\n",
    "    events=sample_indices,\n",
    "    event_labels=np.array(event_labels)\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5ece9ece",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The `Circular` object has a plotting function, so we can visualise the phase angles at the time of the events. This will allow us to see how the phase angles are distributed across the different event types."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "id": "9c2800a4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x1400 with 12 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# find unique labels\n",
    "unique_labels = np.unique(circ.labels)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(\n",
    "    4, len(unique_labels)//4, \n",
    "    figsize=(12, 14), \n",
    "    subplot_kw={'projection': 'polar'}, \n",
    "    sharey=True, sharex=True\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "for ax, label in zip(axes.flatten(), unique_labels):\n",
    "    circplot_tmp = CircPlot(\n",
    "        circ=circ[label],\n",
    "        ax=ax,\n",
    "        title=label\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "    circplot_tmp.add_points(s = 3, alpha = 0.6)\n",
    "    circplot_tmp.add_density()\n",
    "    circplot_tmp.add_histogram(phase)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n"
   ]
  }
 ],
